Zoran Zaev, Prime Minister of Macedonia, his wife Zorica and son Dushko filed their vote in the Macedonian referendum on a change of name of the country that would open the way to join NATO and the European Union in Strumica (Macedonia) on September 30, 2018.
In front of Parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, was preparing a small stage and removing chairs in front of the tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
"We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads high, not through the back door," Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want us to enter as Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership would bring the investment Macedonia so much needs, whose unemployment rate is more than 20 percent.
"I think the vast majority will be in favour, as more than 80% of the citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be a “confirmation of our future.”
A poll published last Monday by the Institute for Policy Research said that between 30 and 43 percent of voters were going to participate in the referendum, which means a smaller turnout than required.
