John Edward: Language Competencies are Essential for the Citizens of the World
Scotland’s independent educational centres have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary exam results that is reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is noted that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, it reaches to his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can observe that languages are at the top of the ranking tables, with the highest rates of approved in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that are part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages as a fundamental competence that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, as a subject, languages are considered to be at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills revealed that, of the reasons given by employers for the difficulties they encountered in covering jobs, 17 % were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Potential job opportunities that require languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically get ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you will always be able to choose between several languages taught by teaching staff specialized in this field.
Scotland’s independent educational centres dedicate all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At the moment, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages remain vitally important for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered “competencies for international communication”.
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to Scotland’s youth.
You have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
