On Saturday, North Korea’s foreign minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of the sanctions deepened its mistrust in the United States and that there was no possibility that his country would unilaterally renounce nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the international body that North Korea had taken "important measures of goodwill" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear testing facilities and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we have not received any similar response from the United States," he said.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence in our national security, and under those circumstances, there’s no chance that we will disarm unilaterally first.”
Although Ri repeated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important, as he did not without further ado reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump following the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work for “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” and Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose coercively, including by objecting to a declaration of war termination,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader announced at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between Kim and Moon Jae, the leader of South Korea, over the past five months, and added: “If South Korea had been the party interested in denuclearization instead of the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stagnation.”
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles toward U.S. soil after “malign president” Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim “rocket man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in advancing disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions needed to continue until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no set deadline for this: “It may take two years, three years, or five months, no matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its progress.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo reported to the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without default until we realize definitive and fully verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang's ballistic and nuclear missile programmes.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
