Syria ready for refugees to return, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has already been going on for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country’s conditions were improving.
“The situation on the ground today is more stable and safe thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists in an attempt to restore normality.
All conditions for the voluntary return of refugees who had to leave the country due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods are already in place.
The UN estimates that since the start of the war in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country who need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would be grateful for the help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from the countries that promoted the insurgency.
