Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decrease
The new report of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends approximately along 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
Over the past week, average concentrations in Pinellas County and its coast have been reported, concentrations between low and high on the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, bottom to low concentrations in Colsota County, and bottom to high concentrations in Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritation problems are still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation problems in the northwestern Florida area over the past week.
